RULES AND REGULATIONS GOVERNING CRUDE TRANSPORTATION BY PIPELINE Rule 5 Definitions “API” means American Petroleum Institute. “ASTM” means ASTM International f/k/a American Society for Testing and Materials. “ASTM D6377” means the standard test method for determination of vapor pressure of crude oil at 100°F, at a 4:l V/L ratio: VPCRx (Expansion Method). “Barrel” means a volume of forty-two (42) United States Gallons at sixty degrees (60°) Fahrenheit and zero (0) gauge pressure if the vapor pressure of the petroleum is at or below atmospheric pressure, or at equilibrium vapor pressure if the vapor pressure of the petroleum is greater than atmospheric pressure. “BPD” means Barrels per day. “Carrier” means Canyon Crossing LLC. “Committed Shipper” means a Shipper that has executed a TSA in the Open Season. “Committed Volume” means a Committed Shipper’s “Committed Volume” designated in its TSA. “Consignee” means the party, including a connecting pipeline system, to whom Shipper has ordered Delivery of Crude Petroleum. “Crude Petroleum” means the direct liquid products of oil wells or a mixture of the direct liquid products of oil wells with indirect liquid products and being similarly transportable as the direct liquid products that meets the quality specifications set forth in Rule 10, provided that such mixture does not contain more than one percent (1%) of sediment, water, and other impurities. “Delivery” means the transfer of custody of Crude Petroleum from Carrier at a Destination Point to Consignee. “Destination Point” means the inlet flange of the destination point set out in the Table of Rates. “Incentive Committed Rate” means the per Barrel rate for a Committed Volume tier of at least 60,000 BPD set out in the Table of Rates, applicable for volumes above 60,000 BPD. “Nomination” means a request by Shipper to Carrier to transport a stated quantity of Crude Petroleum on Carrier’s system for the account of such Shipper in any month. “Notice of Intent to Ship” has the meaning set out in Rule 90 herein. “Open Season” means the open season held by Carrier for Carrier’s system that commenced October 5th, 2020. “Origin Point” means an origin point set out in the Table of Rates. “Priority Service” has the meaning set out in the Proration Policy. “Priority Service Rate” means the per Barrel rate for Priority Service for a Committed Volume tier set out in the Table of Rates. “Proration Policy” means the proration policy set out in Annex I. “Receipt” means the transfer of custody of Crude Petroleum from Shipper at an Origin Point(s) to Carrier for transportation. “Required Inventory” means each Shipper’s proportionate share of the volume of Crude Petroleum, by grade, required by Carrier for line fill and working stock. “Ruby Station” means Carrier’s Ruby Station Origin Point in Major County, Oklahoma. “Shipper” means the party who contracts with Carrier for the transportation of Crude Petroleum under the terms of this tariff. “Shipper’s Inventory” means total Receipts of Crude Petroleum, by grade, from a single Shipper less that Shipper’s Deliveries. “TSA” means a transportation services agreement entered into between Carrier and a Shipper in connection with the Open Season pursuant to which a shipper agrees to ship or pay for a minimum volume commitment for transportation of Crude Petroleum on Carrier’s system. “Uncommitted Rate” means the per Barrel rate for Uncommitted Shippers set out in the Table of Rates. “Uncommitted Shipper” means any Shipper that is not a Committed Shipper. Rule 10 Quality Specifications and Restrictions 1. Shipper shall not tender and Carrier reserves the right to reject, without limitation, any or all of the following: crude oil having (1) a vapor pressure in excess of the maximum pounds per square inch absolute at l00°F indicated in the table below, using the ASTM D6377 test method, or that would result in Carrier’s non-compliance with any federal, state, or local requirements regarding hydrocarbon emissions, (2) an API (American Petroleum Institute) gravity in excess of 60°; (3) an API gravity less than 18.5°; (4) a sulfur content weight percentage greater than 4.15%; (5) sediment and water and other impurities exceeding 1% by volume including not more than five-tenths percent (0.5%) water and/or (6) been contaminated by the presences of (a) iron content in excess of 75ppm as tested by EPA method 3040, (b) organic chlorides in excess of 1ppm as tested by Microcoulometry of Sodium Biphenyl methods, (c) trace metals, chemicals, salts, refinery or chemical plant process or by-product materials in excess of the expected limits of the surrounding producing fields, (d) any other material that may adversely affect the refining process as determined by Carrier, or (e) chemicals foreign to virgin crude oil including but not limited to chlorinated and/or oxygenated hydrocarbons and salt which would adversely affect downstream markets or pipelines or other shippers. Notwithstanding the foregoing Carrier will endeavor to accept crude oil with API gravity of no less than 17° which is less than 18.5° when permissible from connecting facilities at the Origin Point. 2. Shipper shall also not Deliver, and Carrier reserves the right to reject without limitation, any Crude Petroleum that (1) is not readily susceptible to transportation through Carrier’s system, (2) may materially and adversely affect the quality of crude oil from other Shippers, or (3) may cause disadvantage to other Shippers or Carrier, including by having such characteristics as would be expected to cause a reasonable refusal to receive crude oil by a third party terminal or pipeline at the Destination Point. 3. Carrier shall endeavor to deliver substantially the same type of Crude Petroleum as that received from a Shipper. 4. Shipper shall provide adequate storage and other facilities for measuring, testing, collecting, and tendering sufficient Crude Petroleum for aggregation of minimum batch volumes for tender to Carrier at the mainline hourly throughput rates of the segment to which Customer’s volumes are to be tendered. Carrier does not have facilities for rendering, nor does it offer, storage services, except as otherwise specified on a specific rate tariff. Carrier will determine and advise Shippers of the facilities to be provided to meet the operating conditions of Carrier’s facilities. Carrier will not accept Crude Petroleum for transportation unless such facilities have been provided. 5. If Shipper delivers Crude Petroleum to Carrier’s system that does not comply with the quality specifications of this Rule 10, Carrier may exclude such Shipper from further entry into Carrier’s system until such time as the quality of the Crude Petroleum is to the satisfaction of Carrier. Carrier is not responsible for monitoring Receipts or Deliveries for contaminants. Further, in addition to Carrier’s rights to assess demurrage fees in accordance with Rule 55, if Shipper has not removed contaminated Crude Petroleum from Carrier’s system within forty-eight (48) hours of receiving written notice Carrier reserves the right to dispose of any contaminated Crude Petroleum blocking Carrier’s system. Disposal thereof may be made in any reasonable manner including but not limited to commercial sales, and any liability associated with the contamination or disposal of any Crude Petroleum shall be borne by Shipper introducing the contaminated Crude Petroleum into Carrier’s system. Shipper liability includes, but is not limited to, claims from other Shippers, carriers, or users of the contaminated Crude Petroleum and the costs of any regulatory or judicial proceedings.
Rule 15 Origin and Destination Facilities Carrier shall accept Crude Petroleum only when Shipper has provided the necessary equipment and facilities for receipt of Crude Petroleum into Carrier’s System and delivery of Crude Petroleum from Carrier’s System at pressures and pumping rates required by Carrier. The cost of such facilities shall be provided at the sole cost of Shipper seeking access to Carrier’s System. Carrier may require evidence showing that the necessary facilities are available for delivering shipments onto Carrier’s System at the Origin Point(s) and receiving shipments from Carrier’s System at the Destination Point(s) before any obligation to furnish transportation service shall arise. Carrier shall not accept Crude Petroleum at any location other than an Origin Point. Rule 20 Measurements: Gauging or Metering and Testing 1. Subject to paragraph 2 regarding measurement of water, sediment or other impurities all measurement and sampling equipment, procedures and processes, calculations, provings and calibrations, sampling, testing and analysis shall be performed in accordance with the latest applicable API MPMS, ASTM International and NIST (National Institute of Standards and Testing) standards. All shipments tendered to Carrier for transportation shall be gauged, or metered and tested by a representative of Carrier, or by automatic equipment approved by Carrier, prior to, or at the same time as, Receipt from Shipper. Shipper or Consignee shall have the privilege of being present or represented during the gauging, metering, meter proving, calibration and testing. Shipper will grant Carrier’s representative and any applicable connecting carrier’s representative access to Shipper’s facility for witnessing meter or gauge readings, calibration or meter proving and for any other required inspection incidental to measurement and transportation of Crude Petroleum. 2. The full percentage of water, sediment or other impurities as ascertained by a centrifuge machine or other tests will be deducted from the correct volume. Water content shall be determined by API MPMS Ch 10.4 or 10.3 Centrifuge method, with any discrepancies to be resolved by API MPMS Ch. 10.9 Karl Fisher method. Sediment content shall be determined by API MPMS Ch. 10.4 or 10.3 Centrifuge method. 3. Subject to any claims of Shipper pursuant to Rule 70, any overage or shortage, including losses resulting from shrinkage, evaporation, other physical loss and interface mixture in any calendar month, will be allocated on a monthly accrual basis among Shippers in the proportion that the total number of Barrels delivered from the entire system, or applicable pipeline segment, for each Shipper bears to the total number of Barrels delivered from the entire system, or applicable pipeline segment, for all Shippers. Consignee shall be entitled to receive only that portion of a Shipper’s shipment remaining after adjusting for said Shipper’s proportion of such overage or shortage, determined as aforesaid. Rule 25 Line Fill and Working Stock Requirements Each Shipper shall furnish its respective Required Inventory by type and volumes as determined by Carrier from time to time. Carrier shall give Shippers prompt notice concerning adjustments in their respective shares of Required Inventory and shall direct Shippers to promptly reduce or increase their Shipper’s Inventory when necessary. Rule 30 Withdrawal of Required Inventory Subject to the provisions of this tariff, a Shipper may withdraw its Required Inventory from Carrier’s system at any time within ninety (90) days subsequent to: (1) Shipper having ceased tendering shipments and notified Carrier in writing that it will no longer tender shipments to Carrier; (2) Shipper balances having been reconciled between Shipper and Carrier; and (3) Shipper having paid Carrier for all services. Rule 35 Fungible Product Stream 1. Carrier shall endeavor to deliver substantially the same type of Crude Petroleum as that received from a Shipper. Carrier shall not be liable for any variations in gravity (density) or quality of Crude Petroleum transported by Carrier and Crude Petroleum will be accepted for transportation only on the condition that it shall be subject to normal changes in general characteristics while in transit as may result from the mixture of such Crude Petroleum with other Crude Petroleum in the pipeline of Carrier. Carrier is under no obligation to Deliver the identical Crude Petroleum as received. Rule 40 Clear Title Required Carrier shall have the right to reject, on a non-discriminatory basis, any Crude Petroleum when tendered for transportation that is involved in litigation, or the title of which is in dispute, or that is encumbered by lien or charge of any kind (except for the lien provided for in Rule 60). Carrier may require Shipper to provide satisfactory evidence of its perfect and unencumbered title or may require Shipper to furnish a satisfactory indemnity bond to protect Carrier before Carrier is obligated to accept Crude Petroleum for shipment hereunder. Rule 45 Intermediate Delivery A Shipper that nominates Crude Petroleum for transportation from the GMP/NGL-Cushing Origin Point to the Destination Point may request that the Carrier deliver its Crude Petroleum to the intermediate delivery point of Ruby Station for up to a 12-month period, or longer if Carrier provides prior written approval, provided that in connection with such services Carrier is not providing Shipper any storage services at Ruby Station, and Shipper is required to make arrangements for storage with either the third­party owner of Ruby Station or another storage facility connected to Ruby Station, to allow this intermediate delivery. Shipper will be charged the rate associated with movement to its nominated Destination Point, along with any other charges associated with a completed transportation movement (e.g. overages and shortages in accordance with Rule 20). Within that 12-month period (which Carrier may extend by providing prior written approval), Shipper must nominate its Crude Petroleum for delivery to the Destination Point identified in its original nomination. Carrier will transport such Crude Petroleum to the Destination Point, as soon as feasibly possible subject to operating conditions. The re-originated Barrels will not be eligible for Priority Service and Shipper will not be liable to pay an additional fee or tariff for delivery to the Destination Point. Except as otherwise provided above, nominations for re­origination will be subject to the same specifications, obligations and limitations as initial nominations under the Rules and Regulations referenced herein. Rule 55 Deliveries and Demurrage 1. Carrier will transport Crude Petroleum with reasonable diligence, considering the quality of the Crude Petroleum, the distance of transportation, and other material elements, but may at any time after Receipt of a consignment of Crude Petroleum, upon twenty-four (24) hours’ notice to the Consignee, tender Crude Petroleum conformable to specifications herein for Delivery from its common stock at the Destination Point. At the expiration of such notice, Carrier may assess a demurrage charge on all Crude Petroleum tendered for Delivery and remaining undelivered, at the rate for each day of 24 hours, or fractional part thereof, of [I] fifty-two and sixty hundredths cents ($0.5260) per Barrel per day. 2. In addition to charging the demurrage charge above, Carrier may also seek the most expeditious means to divert or dispose of the Crude Petroleum that Shipper has failed to take. Such disposition includes the right to sell the Crude Petroleum at private or public sale. Carrier may be a purchaser at such public sale. From the proceeds of any such sale, Carrier may pay itself all transportation and other charges and expenses in caring for and maintaining the Crude Petroleum and the costs of sale, and the balance shall be held for whomsoever may be lawfully entitled thereto. Rule 60 Payment of Transportation and Other Charges 1. Transportation charges will be computed and collected at the applicable tariff rate (in effect on the date of Receipt of Crude Petroleum by Carrier) on the Receipt quantities of Crude Petroleum determined pursuant to this tariff. Carrier will invoice Shipper for transportation charges on a monthly basis. Shipper shall be responsible for transportation and all other charges applicable to the particular shipment, and, if required, shall prepay all charges or furnish guaranty of payment satisfactory to Carrier. Shipper shall pay all undisputed charges within the later of ten (10) days of the date of invoice from Carrier or the twentieth (20th) day of the month following the month of Delivery. All charges that remain unpaid for more than thirty (30) days from the date of Carrier’s invoice shall accrue an interest charge of the lesser of (i) two percent (2%) above the per annum rate of interest announced from time to time as the “prime rate” for commercial loans by The Wall Street Journal, as such “prime rate” may change from time to time, or (ii) the maximum non-usurious interest rate which may then be charged under Texas law. 2. Carrier shall have a security interest in all Crude Petroleum accepted from Shipper under this tariff. This security interest shall secure: (1) all transportation and any other charges due or to become due from Shipper under the terms of this tariff; (2) all deficiency payments or other obligations due from a shipper entering into a transportation services agreement with Carrier; and (3) all costs and expenses of Carrier in exercising any of its rights detailed herein, including, but not limited to, reasonable attorney fees, storage charges, and settlement of conflicting liens. At Carrier’s request, Shipper shall execute all such agreements and do all such things as Carrier shall reasonably request in connection with the creation or perfection of such security interest. The security interest provided herein shall be in addition to any lien provided by statute or common law. 3. In the event Shipper fails to satisfy when due any payment obligation to Carrier, Carrier shall have all of the rights and remedies accorded to a secured party under applicable state law and in addition may in its sole discretion and without notice take any or all of the following actions: (1) refuse to Deliver Crude Petroleum in its custody until all such obligations have been paid; (2) proceed to sell such Crude Petroleum, in accordance with the applicable provisions of state law, and apply the proceeds to such obligations, (3) store such Crude Petroleum or contract for storage of such Crude Petroleum pending sale or other disposition. Carrier may agree, in its sole discretion, to waive its security interest in the Crude Petroleum if Shipper or Consignee provides sufficient security satisfactory to Carrier. Rule 65 Proration of Pipeline Capacity If, during any period, the total volume of Crude Petroleum nominated over any segment or portion of Carrier’s system is in excess of the amount that can be immediately transported over said segment, Carrier shall allocate transportation capacity in accordance with the Proration Policy. Rule 70 Liabilities of Parties 1. As a condition to Carrier’s acceptance of Crude Petroleum under this tariff, each Shipper agrees to protect and indemnify Carrier against claims or actions for injury and/or death of any and all persons and for damage to property of, or any other loss sustained by Carrier, Shipper, Consignee and/or any third party to the extent resulting from 1) any breach of or failure to adhere to any provision of this tariff by Shipper, Consignee, their agents, employees or representatives and/or 2) the negligent act(s) or failure(s) to act of Shipper, Consignee, their agents, employees or representatives in connection with Delivery or Receipt of Crude Petroleum. 2. Carrier will not be liable for discoloration, contamination, or deterioration of the Crude Petroleum transported hereunder unless and to the extent such discoloration, contamination, or deterioration of Crude Petroleum transported results from the negligence, gross negligence or willful misconduct of Carrier. 3. Carrier, while in possession of Crude Petroleum herein described, shall not be liable for any loss of Crude Petroleum, except to the extent resulting from the negligence, gross negligence or willful misconduct of Carrier; damage thereto; or delay in Delivery because of any act of God, the public enemy, civil disorder, quarantine, the authority of laws, strikes, riots, fire, floods or the acts of default of Shipper or Consignee, or from any other causes not due to the negligence of Carrier. CARRIER WILL NOT BE LIABLE FOR SPECIAL, CONSEQUENTIAL OR INCIDENTAL DAMAGES. FOR THE AVOIDANCE OF DOUBT, DEFICIENCY REVENUE PAYMENTS UNDER A TRANSPORTATION SERVICES AGREEMENT WITH A SHIPPER SHALL BE DEEMED DIRECT DAMAGES AND NOT EXCLUDED BY THIS RULE 70. Rule 75 Notice of Claims As a condition precedent to recovery, claims must be filed in writing with Carrier within nine (9) months after Delivery of Crude Petroleum, or, in case of failure to make Delivery, then within nine (9) months after a reasonable time for Delivery has elapsed; and suits shall be instituted against Carrier only within two (2) years and one (1) day from the day when Delivery was made, or, in case of failure to make Delivery, when Delivery should have been made. All claims and suits not filed or instituted within such time periods shall be forever barred. Rule 80 Intrasystem Transfers Intrasystem transfers will not be recognized by Carrier for Crude Petroleum in Carrier’s custody, except for transfers resulting from application of Rule No. 40 (Clear Title Required) herein. Rule 90 Nominations and Tenders 1. Shippers desiring to nominate Crude Petroleum for transportation by Carrier shall provide Carrier with written notice of the type, expressly including API gravity and if any Crude Petroleum will be less than 20 degrees API gravity, origin, destination and quantity of its Nomination (“Notice of Intent to Ship”). Shippers shall promptly provide Carrier with all other information requested by Carrier to confirm that the Nominations and the proposed shipment will comply in all respects with this tariff. Notices of Intent to Ship must be received by Carrier via email or facsimile transmission on or before 12:00 Noon Central Standard Time/Central Daylight Saving Time, whichever is applicable, the twentieth (20th) day of the month preceding the month during which shipment is requested (“the Nomination Deadline”). Should the Nomination deadline fall on a weekend or holiday, nominations will be due by noon the prior working day. A “working day” shall be a Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday or Friday of a calendar week, except when a Federal holiday falls on such day of the week. 2. The minimum amount of Crude Petroleum that Carrier will accept for transportation from any one Shipper under this tariff from any Origin Point other than a truck injection Origin Point, is ninety thousand (90,000) Barrels; provided that Carrier may accept batches of less than ninety thousand (90,000) Barrels if operationally possible and acceptance may be done so in a non-discriminatory manner. 3. Carrier will not be obligated to make any Single Delivery, as defined in this Rule 90, that is less than the current minimum batch size unless Carrier’s operations dictate otherwise. The term “Single Delivery” in this Rule 90 means a Delivery of Crude Petroleum, in one continuous operation to one Shipper or Consignee into a single facility, furnished by such Shipper or Consignee, to which Carrier is connected. 4. Before Carrier will accept a Notice of Intent to Ship from a New Shipper, such Shipper must (a) comply with the requirements of Carrier regarding creditworthiness and financial assurances, including those set forth in this tariff, (b) demonstrate to Carrier the adequacy of such Shipper’s facilities, and (c) provide any information reasonably requested by Carrier. 5. At all times, Carrier may refuse to accept Crude Petroleum for transportation if Shipper is not in compliance with other provisions of this tariff or where Shipper has failed to comply with all applicable Law regulating shipments of Crude Petroleum. 6. Carrier shall confirm acceptance of nominations, including any adjustment to the Nominations in accordance with Rule 65, on or before on the third (3rd) working day following the Nomination Deadline. Carrier shall evaluate Customer’s request for adjustment to nominations following the Nomination Deadline on a non-discriminatory basis. Rule 95 Pipeage Contracts Carrier may require separate pipeage contracts from Shipper prior to Carrier providing transportation services hereunder, which may include additional charges for reimbursement for facilities necessary to receive or deliver Shipper’s shipments. Rule 105 Truck Loading and Unloading Shipments unloaded from tank trucks into Carrier’s facilities are subject to a per-Barrel charge as specified on the Table of Rates. Such charge will be in addition to all other charges. Rule 110 Financial Assurances At any time, upon the request of Carrier, on a non-discriminatory basis, any prospective or existing Shipper shall provide Carrier with information that Carrier may request to allow Carrier to enforce the terms of this tariff. Such information must be provided within five (5) business days of such request and may include, but is not limited to, the legal business name and the registered business address of the Shipper or prospective Shipper and any affiliates of the Shipper or prospective Shipper. Carrier shall not be obligated to accept Crude Petroleum for transportation from an existing or prospective Shipper (a) if the Shipper or prospective Shipper fails to provide the requested information to Carrier in accordance with this Rule No. 110 within the time periods set forth herein; (b) if Carrier reasonably determines that any of the information provided is false; or, (c) if Carrier’s review of the requested information reveals that the existing or prospective Shipper may not have the capacity to perform the financial obligations that could arise from the transportation of that Shipper’s Crude Petroleum under the terms of this tariff, including but not limited to the payment of transportation charges and other costs and charges hereunder. Subject to the provisions of the paragraph below, Carrier, upon notice to the prospective or existing Shipper, may require one or more of the following financial assurances (“Financial Assurances”) for the payment of all charges and costs as provided for in this tariff, or otherwise lawfully due to Carrier to be provided at the expense of the Shipper: a. prepayment; b. a letter of credit in favor of Carrier in an amount determined by Carrier to ensure payment of all costs and charges that could reasonably accrue due to Carrier in a form and from an institution acceptable to Carrier; c. a guaranty in an amount determined by Carrier to ensure payment of all such costs and charges that could reasonably accrue due to Carrier, in a form and from a third party acceptable to Carrier; or d. such other enforceable collateral security including but not limited to security agreements over assets of the Shipper, in a form acceptable to Carrier. ln the event that Carrier reasonably determines that: a. the existing or prospective Shipper’s financial condition is or has become impaired or unsatisfactory; b. any Financial Assurances previously provided by a Shipper no longer provide adequate security for the performance of the Shipper’s obligations that could arise from the transportation of its Crude Petroleum under the terms of this tariff; or c. Carrier otherwise determines that it is necessary to obtain Financial Assurances from the Shipper, then the Shipper shall provide Financial Assurances for the payment of the charges and costs as provided for in this tariff or otherwise lawfully due to Carrier relating to the transportation of the Shipper’s Crude Petroleum by Carrier. For the purpose of this tariff, and without limiting the generality of the charges and costs lawfully due to Carrier relating to the transportation of the Shipper’s Crude Petroleum, those charges and costs shall include but are not limited to transportation charges and negative Shipper’s balance positions. Carrier shall not be obligated to accept Crude Petroleum for transportation from an existing or prospective Shipper if the Shipper or prospective Shipper fails to deliver the Financial Assurances to Carrier. Rule 115 Shipper Communications 1. At least once per calendar year, Carrier will provide a general update (either via an in-person meeting, conference call or a written communication) to all then-current Shippers regarding the operations of the Subject Pipeline System. This update shall inform Shippers of any recent pipeline downtime, any upcoming major maintenance requiring downtime longer than ninety-six (96) continuous hours, major integrity management plans for the upcoming year, any new projects under development on the Subject Pipeline System and any other relevant updates regarding the Subject Pipeline System that Carrier determines are relevant to share. 2. Carrier agrees to notify Shipper of the occurrence of any accident, incident, violation or which involves Shipper’s titled commodity handled by Carrier or within Carrier’s custody. Both Parties agree to provide commercially reasonable assistance in reviewing the circumstances of the accident, incident or violation. Notifications to Shipper shall be made as soon as reasonably practicable after its occurrence.

Annex I Proration Policy Definitions: The following definitions, in addition to the general definitions in Rule 5, apply to this Annex I: “Adjusted Committed Volume” for a Committed Shipper in any Allocation Month means (1) such Committed Shipper’s Committed Volume, multiplied by (2) Available Capacity for such Allocation Month, and divided by (3) the Available Capacity that would be available in such Allocation Month but for Extraordinary Operating Conditions. “Allocated Capacity” has the meaning set forth in Item H.2. “Allocation Notice” has the meaning set forth in Item A.1 of this Proration Policy. “Allocation Month” means any month in which the Nominations of all Shippers on a specific pipeline segment or portion of Carrier’s system exceed the Available Capacity of such segment or portion, thereby causing Carrier to implement this Proration Policy. “Available Capacity” means the total capacity of Carrier’s system that is available to transport Crude Petroleum in an Allocation Month. The Available Capacity shall be determined by Carrier each Month, but shall always equal, except in Extraordinary Operating Conditions, at least 90,000 Barrels per day from the Origin Points to the Destination Point of WRB Borger, TX, as measured on a Heavy Crude Oil basis. “Base Period” means the fourteen (14) consecutive month period ending with the second month prior to the Allocation Month. “BPM” means barrels per month. “Extraordinary Operating Conditions” means operating conditions that result in the capacity of Carrier’s system, or a segment thereof, being reduced below the Available Capacity of the system, or the applicable segment thereof, for the Allocation Month for any reason, including events of force majeure, weather conditions, repairs or maintenance; provided that any capacity that Carrier determines is not available on its system due to Extraordinary Operating Conditions may not be used by Carrier for any other purpose during such Month. “Heavy Crude Oil” means the grade of Crude Petroleum having the following specifications: (a) API 20-22 degrees; (b) kinematic viscosity <= 350 centistokes at 60° F. “Historic Shipment Ratio” means (i) except as provided below for Non-Priority Committed Shippers, the average BPM transported on a specific pipeline segment or portion of Carrier’s system by a Regular Shipper over the Base Period divided by (ii) the total average BPM of Crude Petroleum transported by all Regular Shippers through that specific segment or portion during the Base Period. The numerator of a Non-Priority Committed Shipper’s Historic Shipment Ratio will be based on the greater of the Barrels that the Non-Priority Shipper shipped or paid a deficiency payment to Carrier for pursuant to its TSA during each Month of the Base Period. (Example: On pipeline segment “A” with a total average volume transported within the Base Period of 100,000 BPM, and a Regular Shipper (who is not a Committed Shipper) has a Base Period shipment history of 40,000 BPM on that pipeline segment, that Regular Shipper’s Historic Shipment Ratio would be 40%.) “New Shipper” means any Shipper that is not a Regular Shipper or a Priority Committed Shipper. “New Shipper Nomination Ratio” means, in any month, a New Shipper’s Nomination divided by the total Nominations of all New Shippers for the Allocation Month. “Notification Period” has the meaning set forth in Item A.2. “Non-Priority Capacity” has the meaning set forth in Item D.1 of this Proration Policy. “Non-Priority Committed Shipper” has the meaning set forth in Item A.2 of this Proration Policy. “Proration Policy” means this Annex I, which is the official written description of the process by which Carrier will allocate Available Capacity when Nominations on any pipeline segment or portion of Carrier’s system exceed the Available Capacity. “Priority Committed Shipper” has the meaning set forth in Item A.2 of this Proration Policy. “Priority Service” means service that is not subject to allocation, except in Extraordinary Operating Conditions. Priority Service is allocated to Priority Committed Shippers under Item C of this Proration Policy. “Regular Shipper” means (a) a Non-Priority Committed Shipper, or (b) an Uncommitted Shipper that has shipped Crude Petroleum to the Destination Point in at least twelve (12) consecutive months during the Base Period. “Uncommitted Shipper Capacity” means ten percent (10%) of Available Capacity. “Unused Allocation” has the meaning set forth in Item H.2. The Allocation Methodology: During an Allocation Month, the Available Capacity on each prorated pipeline segment will be allocated as follows: A. Notification of Allocation and Priority Service Election Right for Committed Shippers l. When it is determined that there is not sufficient Available Capacity to accommodate all valid, timely, and properly submitted Nominations, Carrier will notify each Shipper that has tendered a Nomination for the affected pipeline segment(s) prior to application of the allocation methodology set forth in this Proration Policy (“Allocation Notice”). Upon notification, each Shipper will then have a period of two (2) business days (“Notification Period”) to reduce its Nomination. At 12:01 am on the day immediately following the Notification Period, a Shipper’s adjusted Nomination shall be considered a binding Nomination. 2. During the Notification Period, each Committed Shipper must also notify Carrier of whether it wishes to receive Priority Service at the Priority Committed Rate for its Committed Volume for the Allocation Month. Any election to receive Priority Service must be made with respect to the entirety of a Committed Shipper’s Nomination for the Month, up to the level of its Committed Volume. Any Committed Shipper that elects to receive Priority Service in an Allocation Month shall be referred to as a “Priority Committed Shipper,” while any Committed Shipper that elects not to receive Priority Service in an Allocation Month shall be referred to as a “Non-Priority Committed Shipper”. If a Committed Shipper does not notify Carrier of its election within the Notification Period, then the Committed Shipper will be deemed to have not elected to receive Priority Service for the Allocation Month and will be treated as a Non-Priority Committed Shipper for the Allocation Month for the amount of its Nomination. B. Allocation of Uncommitted Shipper Capacity: 1. Carrier shall first allocate the Uncommitted Shipper Capacity among all Uncommitted Shippers in the following manner. i. Each New Shipper shall be allocated an amount of capacity in the Allocation Month that is equal to: a) its Nomination, if the total volume Nominated by all New Shippers is less than or equal to ten percent (10%) of the Uncommitted Shipper Capacity; or b) its pro rata share, in accordance with its Nomination Ratio, of ten percent (10%) of the Uncommitted Shipper Capacity, if the total volume Nominated by all New Shippers is greater than ten percent (10%) of the Uncommitted Shipper Capacity. c) Carrier shall have the right to increase the Uncommitted Shipper Capacity reserved for New Shippers under this item in the event that Regular Shippers have not submitted Binding Nominations equaling or exceeding ninety percent (90%) of the Uncommitted Capacity. 2. Following the allocation in Item B.1.i, each Regular Shipper who is an Uncommitted Shipper shall be allocated the lesser of (i) its Nomination, or (ii) a fraction of the Uncommitted Shipper Capacity that remains after the allocation to New Shippers, as provided in Item B.l.i, which fraction shall be calculated by multiplying the available remaining Uncommitted Shipper Capacity times the following fraction: the number of Barrels shipped by the Regular Shipper during the Base Period divided by the total number of Barrels shipped during the Base Period by all Regular Shippers who are Uncommitted Shippers and have an unmet Nomination for the Allocation Month. This process will be repeated until all Uncommitted Capacity is consumed or Nominations at issue in this section have been met. For clarity, a Non-Priority Committed Shipper shall not be allocated any capacity under this step of the Proration Policy. C. Allocation of Capacity to Priority Committed Shippers. Carrier shall next allocate each Priority Committed Shipper an amount of capacity that is equal to the lesser of the Priority Committed Shipper’s Adjusted Committed Volume or its Nomination . D. Allocation of Non-Priority Capacity 1. After the allocation in Items B and C above, Carrier shall allocate the remaining Available Capacity (the “Non-Priority Capacity”) among all Regular Shippers, in the following manner: i. each Regular Shipper shall be allocated the lesser of (x) its Nomination, or (y) a portion of the Non-Priority Capacity, which shall be calculated by multiplying the available Non-Priority Capacity times the Historic Shipment Ratio of the Regular Shipper during the Base Period. ii. This process will be repeated until all Non-Priority Capacity is consumed or Nominations of Regular Shippers have been met; provided that the amount of capacity that a Regular Shipper is allocated this subsection plus the amount it is allocated under the other subsections of this Proration Policy shall never exceed the Shipper’s Nomination for the Allocation Month. If that were to occur, then the excess capacity would be reallocated among all other Regular Shippers having unmet Nominations under this Item C. E. Allocation of Remaining Capacity. Any capacity that is not allocated in Items B, C, and D above shall be allocated to any New Shippers having unmet Nominations according to the level of their Nominations for the Allocation Month. This process will be repeated until all of the Nominations of New Shippers have been met. F. If the capacity allocation for any Shipper resulting from the allocation process above is less than the minimum batch size set out in Rule 90, then, to the extent feasible, the Shipper’s allocated capacity will be increased to the minimum batch size of the allocated pipeline segment for the Allocation Month. G. In the event that a Shipper, who in spite of having a binding Nomination on the prorated pipeline segment or portion of Carrier’s system, withdraws that binding Nomination, and as a result the Available Capacity is not fully allocated following application of Items B-E above, the newly available pipeline capacity shall be allocated by applying Item D above again and then Item E (to the extent necessary). H. The following provisions shall apply in each Allocation Month: 1. No movements will be considered above the amount that Shipper has been allocated for shipment, nor will Carrier accept a Nomination that exceeds the Available Capacity. 2. If the allocated capacity awarded to any Uncommitted Shipper on a prorated pipeline segment or portion of Carrier’s system (“Allocated Capacity”) goes unused by that Shipper (“Unused Allocation”), then that Uncommitted Shipper is accountable for payment of the tariff fees for greater of its actual shipments, or ninety-five percent (95%) of its Allocated Capacity. These charges will be waived when there exists Unused Allocation as a result of Deliveries having been reduced at the request of Carrier, or where Extraordinary Operating Conditions prevented full Receipt or Delivery of Barrels tendered by the Shipper. This charge only applies when the pipeline segment or portion of Carrier’s system is in proration. In the event that a Shipper releases all or any part of its Allocated Capacity in sufficient time prior to the Allocation Month to permit Carrier to reallocate and revise the schedule, and as a result Carrier is then able to solicit other Shippers to fully utilize that capacity, then in that event, Shipper’s allocation will be reduced without penalty. 3. Carrier will carefully examine Nominations, using every means available to ensure that they are true and realistic and will challenge any Nominations that appear to be inflated. Carrier may require written assurances from responsible officials of Shippers requesting use of allocated capacity, stating that this requirement has not been violated. In the event any Shipper shall, by any device, scheme, or arrangement whatsoever, make available to another Shipper, or in the event any Shipper shall receive and use any Available Capacity from another Shipper through violation of this Proration Policy, then the allocated capacity for both Shippers will be reduced, to the extent of the allocated capacity so made available or used, in the next Allocation Month after such violation becomes known to Carrier. 4. Except as provided in this Proration Policy, Allocated Capacity and shipment history may not be assigned, conveyed, or transferred to or used in any manner by another Shipper without prior consent of Carrier, which shall not be unreasonably withheld. The only instances where a Shipper’s shipper history and/or Allocated Capacity may be transferred, in whole or in part, are (1) as an incident of the bona fide sale of Shipper’s business or to a successor to Shipper’s business by the operation of law, or (2) to or from an entity that has acted as the exclusive transporter of another entity’s Crude Petroleum production, but only to the extent relating to such production.

RULES AND REGULATIONS GOVERNING CRUDE TRANSPORTATION BY PIPELINE
Rule 5 Definitions
“Barrel” means a volume of forty-two (42) United States Gallons at sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60° F) and zero (0) gauge pressure if the vapor pressure of the petroleum is at or below atmospheric pressure, or at equilibrium vapor pressure if the vapor pressure of the petroleum is greater than atmospheric pressure. “BPD” means Barrels per day. “Carrier” means Canyon Crossing LLC. “Consignee” means the party, including a connecting pipeline system, to whom Shipper has ordered Delivery of Crude Petroleum. “Crude Petroleum” means the direct liquid products of oil wells or a mixture of the direct liquid products of oil wells with indirect liquid products and being similarly transportable as the direct liquid products that meets the quality specifications set forth in Rule 10, provided that such mixture does not contain more than one percent (1%) of sediment, water, and other impurities. “Delivery” means the transfer of custody of Crude Petroleum from Carrier at a Destination Point to Consignee. “Destination Point” means the inlet flange of the destination point set out in the Table of Rates. “Nomination” means a request by Shipper to Carrier to transport a stated quantity of Crude Petroleum on Carrier’s system for the account of such Shipper in any month. “Notice of Intent to Ship” has the meaning set out in Rule 90 herein. “Origin Point” means an origin point set out in the Table of Rates. “Receipt” means the transfer of custody of Crude Petroleum from Shipper at an Origin Point(s) to Carrier for transportation. “Reid Vapor Pressure” means the absolute vapor pressure at one-hundred degrees Fahrenheit (100° F) of volatile Crude Petroleum herein expressed in pounds per square inch, as determined by test method ASTM D-323. “Required Inventory” means each Shipper’s proportionate share of the volume of Crude Petroleum, by grade, required by Carrier for line fill and working stock. “Shipper” means the party who contracts with Carrier for the transportation of Crude Petroleum under the terms of this tariff. “Shipper’s Inventory” means total Receipts of Crude Petroleum, by grade, from a single Shipper less that Shipper’s Deliveries. “Specified Grade” means Crude Petroleum meeting certain specifications designated by Carrier for such grade of Crude Petroleum.
“True Vapor Pressure” or “TVP” means the temperature dependent vapor pressure of crude oil as measured in accordance with ASTM D6377 (most current version), specifically applied as VPCR4(X); provided in the event connecting terminals or carriers adopt a different methodology for measuring True Vapor Pressure, Carrier reserves the right to modify its measurement methodology to conform to connecting terminals or carriers.
Rule 10 Quality Specifications and Restrictions
Subject to agreement between Shipper and Carrier regarding transportation from intermediate points, Carrier will receive Crude Petroleum through its present facilities at only an Origin Point. Shipper shall not tender and Carrier reserves the right to reject, without limitation, any or all of the following: crude oil having (1) a Reid Vapor Pressure in excess of nine (9) pounds per square inch absolute; (2) a True Vapor Pressure in excess of eleven (11) pounds per square inch; (3) an API (American Petroleum Institute) gravity in excess of seventy degrees (70°); (4) an API gravity less than twenty-eight degrees (28°); (5) a sulfur content weight percentage greater than two percent (2.0%); (6) impurities exceeding one percent (1.0%) including not more than three-tenths percent (0.3%) water; and/or (7) been contaminated by the presences of any excess metals including but not limited to chlorinated and/or oxygenated hydrocarbons and salt. If Carrier determines that a Shipper has Delivered to Carrier's facilities crude oil not meeting the foregoing quality specifications, such Shipper will be excluded from further entry into the system until such time as quality specifications have been demonstrated by Shipper to be met. Any liability associated with the contamination or disposal of any crude oil shall be borne by the responsible Shipper.
Shipper shall also not Deliver, and Carrier reserves the right to reject without limitation, any Crude Petroleum that (1) is not readily susceptible to transportation through Carrier’s system, (2) may materially and adversely affect the quality of crude oil from other Shippers, or (3) may cause disadvantage to other Shippers or Carrier, including by having such characteristics as would be expected to cause a reasonable refusal to receive crude oil by a third party terminal or pipeline at the Destination Point.
Carrier will from time to time give notice to Shippers establishing Specified Grades which Carrier will regularly transport as a common stream between each Origin Point and each Destination Point. For the avoidance of doubt, if a Specified Grade has crude quality specifications more restrictive than those generally applicable to Crude Petroleum in this Item No. 10, then Carrier shall apply the more restrictive crude quality specifications for the Specified Grade to Barrels in the common stream for such Specified Grade, as well as the other crude quality specifications generally applicable to Crude Petroleum in this Item No. 10. Shipper shall, at the request of Carrier, make such Specified Grade available in such quantities and at such times as may be necessary to permit such common stream movements. Carrier may from time to time, after reasonable notice to Shippers who have shipped such Specified Grade in the prior three months, cease to transport such Specified Grade as a common stream or change the specifications of a particular Specified Grade transported as a common stream.
At the request of a Shipper, and subject to other provisions of this tariff, Carrier will accept for shipment the following Specified Grade(s), to be transported as a common stream of Crude Petroleum from an Origin Point to a Destination Point.

Carrier is not responsible for monitoring Receipts or Deliveries for contaminants. Further, Carrier reserves the right to dispose of any contaminated Crude Petroleum blocking Carrier’s system. Disposal thereof may be made in any reasonable manner including but not limited to commercial sales, and any liability associated with the contamination or disposal of any Crude Petroleum shall be borne by Shipper introducing the contaminated Crude Petroleum into Carrier’s system. Shipper liability includes, but is not limited to, claims from other Shippers, carriers, or users of the contaminated Crude Petroleum and the costs of any regulatory or judicial proceeding.
Rule 15 Destination Arrangements Required
Carrier will receive Crude Petroleum for transportation (a) when the Crude Petroleum is to be received into Carrier's facilities at an Origin Point and Shipper or Consignee has made arrangements for further transportation beyond the designated Destination Point or (b) when Shipper or Consignee has provided the necessary arrangements for receiving such Crude Petroleum promptly on arrival at the designated Destination Point. Rule 20 Gauging or Metering and Testing
All shipments tendered to Carrier for transportation shall be gauged or metered and tested by a representative of Carrier, or by automatic equipment approved by Carrier, prior to, or at the same time as, Receipt from Shipper. Shipper or Consignee shall have the privilege of being present or represented during the gauging or metering and testing. Shipper will grant Carrier’s representative and any applicable connecting carrier’s representative access to Shipper’s facility for witnessing meter or gauge readings or meter proving and for any other required inspection incidental to measurement and transportation of Crude Petroleum. Quantities gauged or metered shall be corrected from observed temperatures to sixty degrees (60°) Fahrenheit using applicable Standard Petroleum Measurement Tables adopted jointly by the American Petroleum Institute (API Standard 2540) and the American Society for Testing Materials (ASTM Standard D 1250). The full percentage of water or other impurities as ascertained by a centrifuge machine or other tests will be deducted from the correct volume. Actual losses of Crude Petroleum will be deducted monthly. To the extent losses exceed one-tenth of one percent (0.10%), as adjusted below for Crude Petroleum of API gravity higher than fifty degrees (50°), Carrier shall compensate Shipper for each lost Barrel in excess of the maximum allowed with a credit towards shipping fees owed, at a value per Barrel equal to the NYMEX calendar month average for WTI (including weekends and holidays) for the month such Barrel is lost. All Receipts of Crude Petroleum and indirect liquid products having an API gravity of 50 degrees (50°) or above shall be subject to an increase in the one-tenth of one percent (0.10%) cap above to cover shrinkage and evaporation. Such increase shall be determined in accordance with the following table:

Rule 25 Line Fill and Working Stock Requirements
Each Shipper shall furnish its respective Required Inventory by type and volumes as determined by Carrier from time to time. Carrier shall give Shippers prompt notice concerning adjustments in their respective shares of Required Inventory and shall direct Shippers to reduce or increase their Shipper’s Inventory when necessary. Inventory adjustments shall be completed within sixty (60) days after notice. Rule 30 Withdrawal of Required Inventory
Subject to the provisions of this tariff, a Shipper may withdraw its Required Inventory from Carrier’s system at any time within ninety (90) days subsequent to: (1) Shipper having ceased tendering shipments and notified Carrier in writing that it will no longer tender shipments to Carrier; (2) Shipper balances having been reconciled between Shipper and Carrier; and (3) Shipper having paid Carrier for all services.
Rule 35 Fungible Product Stream; Quality Specifications
Crude Petroleum will be accepted for transportation only on condition that it shall be subject to normal changes in general characteristics while in transit as may result from the mixture of such Crude Petroleum with other similar Crude Petroleum in the pipeline and/or tanks of Carrier or connecting carrier. Carrier is under no obligation to Deliver the identical Crude Petroleum as received. Carrier shall Deliver substantially the same grade specifications of such Specified Grade as that received from a Shipper.
Rule 40 Clear Title Required
Carrier shall have the right to reject, on a non-discriminatory basis, any Crude Petroleum when tendered for transportation that is involved in litigation, or the title of which is in dispute, or that is encumbered by lien or charge of any kind. Carrier may require Shipper to provide satisfactory evidence of its perfect and unencumbered title or may require Shipper to furnish a satisfactory indemnity bond to protect Carrier.
Rule 45 Common Stream Petroleum Connecting Carriers
When both Receipts from and/or Deliveries to a connecting carrier of substantially the same Specified Grade are scheduled at the same interconnection, Carrier reserves the right, with cooperation of the connecting carrier, to offset like volumes of such common stream Crude Petroleum. When this right is exercised, Carrier will make Deliveries for Shipper involved from its substantially similar common stream Crude Petroleum.
Rule 50 Application of Rates from/to Intermediate Origin/Destination Points
For Crude Petroleum accepted for transportation from any origin point on Carrier not named in this tariff, which is intermediate to any published Origin Points and/or Destination Points for which rates are published, Carrier will apply from such unnamed origin point the rate published from the next more distant Origin Point specified. If branch or diverging lines create two (2) or more “next most distant points,” Carrier will apply the rate which will result in the lowest charge. For Crude Petroleum accepted for transportation to any destination point on Carrier not named in this tariff which is intermediate to any published Destination Points and/or Origin Points for which rates are published, Carrier will apply to such unnamed destination point the rate published to the next more distant Destination Point specified. If branch or diverging lines create two or more “next most distant points,” Carrier will apply the rate which will result in the lowest charge. Carrier will file a tariff applicable to such transportation movements within thirty (30) days of the start of the service if the intermediate point is to be used on a continuous basis for more than thirty (30) days.
Rule 55 Deliveries and Demurrage
Carrier will transport Crude Petroleum with reasonable diligence, considering the quality of the Crude Petroleum, the distance of transportation, and other material elements, but may at any time after Receipt of a consignment of Crude Petroleum, upon twenty-four (24) hours’ notice to the Consignee, tender Crude Petroleum conformable to specifications herein for Delivery from its common stock at the Destination Point. At the expiration of such notice, Carrier may assess a demurrage charge on all Crude Petroleum tendered for Delivery and remaining undelivered, at the rate for each day of twenty-four (24) hours, or fractional part thereof, as follows: [U] eighty cents ($0.80) per Barrel per day.
Rule 60 Payment of Transportation and Other Charges
Transportation charges will be computed and collected at the applicable tariff rate (in effect on the date of Receipt of Crude Petroleum by Carrier) on the Receipt quantities of Crude Petroleum determined pursuant to this tariff. Carrier will invoice Shipper for transportation charges on a monthly basis. Shipper shall be responsible for transportation and all other charges applicable to the particular shipment, and, if required, shall prepay all charges or furnish guaranty of payment satisfactory to Carrier. Shipper shall pay all charges within the later of ten (10) days of the date of invoice from Carrier or the twentieth (20th) day of the month following the month of Delivery. All charges that remain unpaid for more than 30 days from the date of Carrier’s invoice shall accrue an interest charge of the lesser of (i) two percent (2%) above the per annum rate of interest announced from time to time as the “prime rate” for commercial loans by The Wall Street Journal, as such “prime rate” may change from time to time, or, (ii) the maximum non-usurious interest rate which may then be charged under Texas law. Carrier shall have a security interest in all Crude Petroleum accepted from Shipper under this tariff. This security interest shall secure: (1) all transportation and any other charges due or to become due from Shipper under the terms of this tariff; (2) all deficiency payments or other obligations due from a shipper entering into a transportation services agreement with Carrier; and (3) all costs and expenses of Carrier in exercising any of its rights detailed herein, including, but not limited to, reasonable attorney fees, storage charges, and settlement of conflicting liens. At Carrier’s request, Shipper shall execute all such agreements and do all such things as Carrier shall reasonably request in connection with the creation or perfection of such security interest. The security interest provided herein shall be in addition to any lien provided by statute or common law. In the event Shipper fails to satisfy when due any payment obligation to Carrier, Carrier shall have all of the rights and remedies accorded to a secured party under applicable state law and in addition may in its sole discretion and without notice take any or all of the following actions: (a) refuse to Deliver Crude Petroleum in its custody until all such obligations have been paid; (b) proceed to sell such Crude Petroleum, in accordance with the applicable provisions of state law, and apply the proceeds to such obligations, (c) store such Crude Petroleum or contract for storage of such Crude Petroleum pending sale or other disposition; or (d) take any other action it deems necessary for the proper protection and sale of such Crude Petroleum. Carrier may agree, in its sole discretion, to waive its security interest in the Crude Petroleum if Shipper or Consignee provides sufficient security satisfactory to Carrier.
Rule 65 Proration of Pipeline Capacity
If, during any period, the total volume of Crude Petroleum nominated over any segment or portion of Carrier’s system is in excess of the amount that can be immediately transported over said segment, Carrier shall allocate transportation capacity in accordance with Annex I.
Rule 70 Liabilities of Parties
As a condition to Carrier’s acceptance of Crude Petroleum under this tariff, each Shipper agrees to protect and indemnify Carrier against claims or actions for injury and/or death of any and all persons and for damage to property of, or any other loss sustained by Carrier, Shipper, Consignee and/or any third party resulting from or arising out of (1) any breach of or failure to adhere to any provision of this tariff by Shipper, Consignee, their agents, employees or representatives and/or (2) the negligent act(s) or failure(s) to act of Shipper, Consignee, their agents, employees or representatives in connection with Delivery or Receipt of Crude Petroleum. Carrier, while in possession of Crude Petroleum herein described, shall not be liable for any loss of Crude Petroleum, except as provided in Rule 20; damage thereto; or delay in Delivery because of any act of God, the public enemy, civil disorder, quarantine, the authority of laws, strikes, riots, fire, floods or the acts of default of Shipper or Consignee, or from any other causes not due to the negligence of Carrier. In case of loss or damage from causes other than the negligence of Carrier, subject to Rule 20, such loss or damage shall be charged proportionately to each shipment in the ratio that such shipment, or portion thereof, received and undelivered at the time the loss or damage occurs, bears to the total of all shipments or portions thereof, then in custody of Carrier for transportation via the lines or contained in other facilities in which the loss or damage occur. Consignee shall be entitled to receive only that portion of a Shipper’s shipment remaining after deducting said Shipper’s proportion of such loss or damage, determined as aforesaid, and shall be required to pay transportation charges only on the quantity Delivered. CARRIER WILL NOT BE LIABLE FOR SPECIAL, CONSEQUENTIAL OR INCIDENTAL DAMAGES. FOR THE AVOIDANCE OF DOUBT, DEFICIENCY REVENUE PAYMENTS UNDER A TRANSPORTATION SERVICES AGREEMENT WITH A SHIPPER SHALL BE DEEMED DIRECT DAMAGES AND NOT EXCLUDED BY THIS RULE 70.
Rule 75 Notice of Claims
As a condition precedent to recovery, claims must be filed in writing with Carrier within nine (9) months after Delivery of Crude Petroleum, or, in case of failure to make Delivery, then within nine (9) months after a reasonable time for Delivery has elapsed; and suits shall be instituted against Carrier only within two (2) years and one (1) day from the day when Delivery was made, or, in case of failure to make Delivery, when Delivery should have been made. All claims and suits not filed or instituted within such time periods shall be forever barred.
Rule 80 Intrasystem Transfers
Intrasystem transfers will not be recognized by Carrier for Crude Petroleum in Carrier’s custody, except for transfers resulting from application of Rule No. 40 (Clear Title Required) herein.
Rule 85 Connection Policy
Requests for connections to Carrier’s system will only be considered if made by formal written notification to Carrier. All requests will be subject to the following standards and conditions: (1) all connections will be subject to design requirements necessary to protect the safety, security, integrity and efficient operation of Carrier’s system in accordance with generally accepted industry standards; and (2) acceptance of any request for connection will be subject to compliance with governmental regulations.
Rule 90 Nominations and Tenders
Shippers desiring to nominate Crude Petroleum for transportation by Carrier shall provide Carrier with written notice of the type, origin, destination and quantity of its Nomination (“Notice of Intent to Ship”). Shippers shall promptly provide Carrier with all other information requested by Carrier to confirm that the Nominations and the proposed shipment will comply in all respects with this tariff. Notices of Intent to Ship must be received by Carrier via email or facsimile transmission on or before 12:00 Noon Central Standard Time/Central Daylight Saving Time, whichever is applicable, the last working day prior to twenty-second (22nd) day of the month preceding the month during which shipment is requested. A “working day” shall be a Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday or Friday of a calendar week, except when a Federal holiday falls on such day of the week. The minimum amount of Crude Petroleum that Carrier will accept for transportation from any one Shipper under this tariff from any Origin Point other than a truck injection Origin Point, is fifty thousand (50,000) Barrels; provided that Carrier may accept batches of less than fifty thousand (50,000) Barrels if operationally possible and acceptance may be done so in a non-discriminatory manner. Carrier may, at its sole discretion and in a non-discriminatory manner, revise the minimum batch size set forth in this Rule 90 when necessary to maintain efficient operation of Carrier’s pipeline. Carrier will not be obligated to make any Single Delivery, as defined in this Rule 90, that is less than the current minimum batch size unless Carrier’s operations dictate otherwise. The term “Single Delivery” in this Rule 90 means a Delivery of Crude Petroleum, in one continuous operation to one Shipper or Consignee into a single facility, furnished by such Shipper or Consignee, to which Carrier is connected.
Rule 95 Pipeage Contracts
Carrier may require separate pipeage contracts from Shipper prior to Carrier providing any transportation service hereunder.
Rule 100 Charges for Spill Compensation Acts and Regulations
In addition to the transportation charges and all other charges accruing on Crude Petroleum accepted for transportation hereunder, a per Barrel charge will be assessed and collected in the amount of any tax, fee, or other charge levied against Carrier in connection with such Crude Petroleum by any Federal, state, or local government or agency which levies a tax, fee, or other charge, on the receipt, delivery, transfer, or transportation of such Crude Petroleum within such government’s jurisdiction for the purpose of creating a fund for the prevention, containment, and/or removal of spills and/or reimbursement of persons sustaining loss or damage therefrom, and/or preparation for response to spills.
Rule 105 Truck Loading and Unloading
Shipments unloaded from tank trucks into Carrier’s facilities are subject to a per-Barrel charge as specified on the Table of Rates. Such charge will be in addition to all other charges.
Rule 110 Financial Assurances
At any time, upon the request of Carrier, on a non-discriminatory basis, any prospective or existing Shipper shall provide Carrier with information that Carrier may request to allow Carrier to enforce the terms of this tariff. Such information must be provided within five (5) business days of such request and may include, but is not limited to, the legal business name and the registered business address of the Shipper or prospective Shipper and any affiliates of the Shipper or prospective Shipper.
Carrier shall not be obligated to accept Crude Petroleum for transportation from an existing or prospective Shipper (a) if the Shipper or prospective Shipper fails to provide the requested information to Carrier in accordance with this Rule No. 110 within the time periods set forth herein; (b) if Carrier reasonably determines that any of the information provided is false; or, (c) if Carrier’s review of the requested information reveals that the existing or prospective Shipper may not have the capacity to perform the financial obligations that could arise from the transportation of that Shipper’s Crude Petroleum under the terms of this tariff, including but not limited to the payment of transportation charges and other costs and charges hereunder.
Subject to the provisions of the paragraph below, Carrier, upon notice to the prospective or existing Shipper, may require one or more of the following financial assurances (“Financial Assurances”) for the payment of all charges and costs as provided for in this tariff, or otherwise lawfully due to Carrier to be provided at the expense of the Shipper: a. prepayment; b. a letter of credit in favor of Carrier in an amount determined by Carrier to ensure payment of all costs and charges that could reasonably accrue due to Carrier in a form and from an institution acceptable to Carrier; c. a guaranty in an amount determined by Carrier to ensure payment of all such costs and charges that could reasonably accrue due to Carrier, in a form and from a third party acceptable to Carrier; or d. such other enforceable collateral security including but not limited to security agreements over assets of the Shipper, in a form acceptable to Carrier.
In the event that Carrier reasonably determines that: a. the existing or prospective Shipper’s financial condition is or has become impaired or unsatisfactory; b. any Financial Assurances previously provided by a Shipper no longer provide adequate security for the performance of the Shipper’s obligations that could arise from the transportation of its Crude Petroleum under the terms of this tariff; or c. Carrier otherwise determines that it is necessary to obtain Financial Assurances from the Shipper,
then the Shipper shall provide Financial Assurances for the payment of the charges and costs as provided for in this tariff or otherwise lawfully due to Carrier relating to the transportation of the Shipper’s Crude Petroleum by Carrier.
For the purpose of this tariff, and without limiting the generality of the charges and costs lawfully due to Carrier relating to the transportation of the Shipper’s Crude Petroleum, those charges and costs shall include but are not limited to transportation charges and negative Shipper’s balance positions. Carrier shall not be obligated to accept Crude Petroleum for transportation from an existing or prospective Shipper if the Shipper or prospective Shipper fails to deliver the Financial Assurances to Carrier.

Annex I Proration Policy Definitions:
The following definitions, in addition to the general definitions in Rule 5, apply to this Annex I: “Allocation Month” means any month in which the Nominations of all Shippers on a specific pipeline segment or portion of Carrier’s system exceed the Available Capacity of such segment or portion, thereby causing Carrier to implement this Proration Policy.
“Available Capacity” means the total capacity of a pipeline segment or portion of Carrier’s system that is available to transport Crude Petroleum in an Allocation Month, as determined by Carrier.
“Base Period” means the twelve (12) consecutive month period ending with the second month prior to the Allocation Month.
“BPM” means barrels per month.
“Extraordinary Operating Conditions” means operating conditions which result in the capacity of Carrier’s system available for shipments of Crude Petroleum, or a segment or portion thereof that is used to provide services, being reduced below Available Capacity used for the allocation methodology for any reason, including events of force majeure, weather conditions, repairs or maintenance.
“Historic Shipment Ratio” means the average BPM transported on a specific pipeline segment or portion of Carrier’s system by a Regular Shipper over the Base Period divided by the total average volume of Crude Petroleum transported by all Regular Shippers through that specific segment or portion per month during the Base Period. (Example: On pipeline segment “A” with a total average volume transported within the Base Period of 1,000,000 BPM, and a Regular Shipper with a Base Period history of transporting 400,000 BPM on that pipeline segment, that Regular Shipper's Historic Shipment Ratio would be 40%.)
“New Shipper” means any Shipper that is not a Regular Shipper.
“New Shipper Capacity” means ten percent (10%) of Available Capacity.
“Nomination Ratio” means, in any month, a Shipper’s Nomination volume divided by the total of all Shippers’ Nomination volumes.
“Proration Policy” means this Annex I, which is the official written description of the process by which Carrier will allocate Available Capacity when Nominations on any pipeline segment or portion of Carrier’s system exceed the Available Capacity.
“Regular Shipper” means a Shipper that has shipped Crude Petroleum in at least ten (10) months during the Base Period.
“Remaining Nomination” means a Shipper’s Nomination for an Allocation Month, less such Shipper’s allocated capacity following application of Items No. 1-2 below.
“Remaining Nomination Ratio” means a Shipper’s Remaining Nomination divided by the total of all Shipper’s Remaining Nominations.
The Allocation Methodology:
During an Allocation Month, Available Capacity on each prorated pipeline segment will be allocated as follows:
A. In any Allocation Month that occurs during the first fourteen months of operation of the Carrier’s pipeline (i.e., prior to the establishment of the initial Base Period):
1. Carrier will allocate each Shipper who submitted a Nomination for transportation a portion of the Available Capacity of the prorated pipeline segment, which amount shall be determined by multiplying such Shipper's Nomination Ratio for the Allocation Month by the Available Capacity of the prorated pipeline segment. 2. In the event that a Shipper, who in spite of having a binding Nomination on the prorated pipeline segment or portion of Carrier’s system, withdraws that binding Nomination, and as a result the Available Capacity is not fully allocated following application of Item No. 1 above, the newly available pipeline capacity shall be allocated by applying Item No. 1 above again, with each Shipper’s Nomination reduced for any capacity previously allocated pursuant to Item No. 1.
B. During any Allocation Month following the establishment of the initial Base Period:
1. Carrier will first allocate the New Shipper Capacity among all New Shippers, with each New Shipper receiving the lesser of its pro rata share of the New Shipper Capacity or its Nomination for the Allocation Month; provided that, under this Item No. 1, no New Shipper will be allocated more than two-and-one-halfpercent (2.5%) of the Available Capacity of the pipeline segment being allocated. To the extent feasible, a New Shipper’s allocated capacity will not be less than the minimum batch size set out in Carrier’s tariff.
2. Carrier shall next allocate the remaining Available Capacity of the pipeline segment being allocated to all Regular Shippers, with each Regular Shipper receiving an amount of capacity equal to the lesser of its Nomination or the Regular Shipper's Crude Petroleum Historic Shipment Ratio multiplied by the remaining Available Capacity of the prorated pipeline segment. If the result of the allocation calculation for a Regular Shipper in Item No. 2 is less than the minimum batch size set out in Rule 90, then, to the extent feasible, the Regular Shipper’s allocated capacity will be increased to the minimum batch size of the allocated pipeline segment for the Allocation Month.
3. If there is any Available Capacity remaining after completion of Item Nos. 1-2, each Shipper having an unmet Nomination will be allocated a portion of remaining Available Capacity, with such amount equaling the Shipper’s Remaining Nomination Ratio multiplied by the remaining Available Capacity.
4. In the event that a Shipper, who in spite of having a binding Nomination on the prorated pipeline segment, attempts to withdraw that binding Nomination, and as a result the Available Capacity is not fully allocated following application of Item Nos. 1 through 3 above, the newly Available Capacity shall be allocated by applying Item No. 3 above again, with each Shipper’s Remaining Nomination reduced for any capacity previously allocated pursuant to Item No. 3.
C. The following provisions shall apply in each Allocation Month:
1. When it is determined that there is insufficient Available Capacity to accommodate all valid, timely, and properly submitted Nominations, Carrier will so notify each Shipper that has tendered a Nomination for the affected pipeline segment(s) prior to application of the allocation methodology. On notification each Shipper will then have a period of two (2) business days to reduce its Nomination. At 12:01 am on the third (3rd) business day following the day notification was made to a Shipper, this adjusted Nomination shall be considered a binding Nomination.
2. No movements will be considered above the amount that Shipper has been allocated for shipment, nor will Carrier accept a Nomination which exceeds the Available Capacity.
3. If the allocated capacity awarded to a Regular Shipper or New Shipper on a prorated pipeline segment or portion of Carrier’s system goes unused by that Shipper (“Unused Allocation”), then that Shipper is accountable for payment of the tariff fees for the actual shipments, or ninety-five percent (95%) of its allocated capacity, whichever is greater. These charges will be waived when there exists Unused Allocation as a result of Deliveries having been reduced at the request of Carrier, or where Extraordinary Operating Conditions prevented full Receipt or Delivery of Barrels tendered by the Shipper. This charge only applies when the pipeline segment or portion of Carrier’s system is in proration.
4. In the event that a Regular Shipper or New Shipper releases all or any part of its allocated capacity in sufficient time prior to the Allocation Month to permit Carrier to reallocate and revise the schedule, and as a result Carrier is then able to solicit other Shippers to fully utilize that capacity, that Shipper's allocation will be reduced without penalty.
5. Carrier will carefully examine Nominations, using every means available to ensure that they are true and realistic and will challenge any Nominations that appear to be inflated. Carrier may require written assurances from responsible officials of Shippers requesting use of allocated capacity, stating that this requirement has not been violated. In the event any Shipper shall, by any device, scheme, or arrangement whatsoever, make available to another Shipper, or in the event any Shipper shall receive and use any Available Capacity from another Shipper through violation of this Proration Policy, then the allocated capacity for both Shippers will be reduced, to the extent of the allocated capacity so made available or used, in the next Allocation Month after such violation becomes known to Carrier. In the event of sale, merger, consolidation or other material occurrence affecting a Shipper, Carrier shall make adjustments in allocations consistent with this Proration Policy.
6. Except as provided in this Proration Policy, prorated transportation capacity allocated to a Shipper and shipment history may not be assigned, conveyed, or transferred to or used in any manner by another Shipper. However, a Shipper’s allocation may be transferred, in whole or in part, (1) as an incident of the bona fide sale of Shipper’s business or to a successor to Shipper’s business by the operation of law or (2) to or from an entity that has acted as the exclusive transporter of another entity’s Crude Petroleum production, but only to the extent relating to such production. Nothing set out herein restricts or impairs Shipper’s ability to enter into buy-sell transactions or other similar arrangements subject to the terms of Carrier’s tariff.
